<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[187,1399,1700,1832]" pageId="9" pageNumber="103">
The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[240,354,1700,1726]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Muscidae</taxonomicName>
with ca 5000 described species represent one of the largest radiations among the calyptrate families. The classification adopted here is fairly conventional, morphology based, but slightly updated according to results obtained from analyses of molecular data presented in particular by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kutty S. N. &amp; Pont A. C. &amp; Meier R. &amp; Pape T." pageId="9" pageNumber="103" pagination="349 - 364" refId="ref14758" refString="Kutty S. N., Pont A. C., Meier R. &amp; Pape T. 2014. Complete tribal sampling reveals basal split in Muscidae (Muscidae), confirms saprophagy as ancestral feeding mode, and reveals an evolutionary correlation between instar numbers and carnivory. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 78: 349 - 364. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2014.05.027" type="journal article" year="2014">
Kutty 
<emphasis box="[1337,1399,1770,1796]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="103">et al.</emphasis>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
. It recognizes eight subfamilies, seven tribes and 179 genus-group taxa (
<tableCitation box="[1121,1209,1805,1832]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[189,258,265,291]" captionTargetBox="[238,1379,394,1980]" captionText="Table 1 (continued on next 4 pages). Summary of vein C chaetotaxy with respect to multistate characterA for genus-group taxa of Fanniidae Schnabel &amp; Dziedcicki, 1911 and Muscidae Latreille, 1802. Examined genera highlighted in yellow. See ‘Material and methods’ for explanation of character states A0–8." pageId="9" pageNumber="103">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[188,1398,1871,1967]" pageId="9" pageNumber="103">
Species from 115 muscid genera and subgenera have presently been examined for the distribution of setulae ventrally and dorsally on vein C (character 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[782,803,1906,1932]" pageId="9" pageNumber="103">A</emphasis>
) in agreement with the nine states described above (
<tableCitation box="[196,284,1941,1967]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[189,258,265,291]" captionTargetBox="[238,1379,394,1980]" captionText="Table 1 (continued on next 4 pages). Summary of vein C chaetotaxy with respect to multistate characterA for genus-group taxa of Fanniidae Schnabel &amp; Dziedcicki, 1911 and Muscidae Latreille, 1802. Examined genera highlighted in yellow. See ‘Material and methods’ for explanation of character states A0–8." pageId="9" pageNumber="103">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
